<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="291" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,441,467]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is a noun in apposition derived from the name of the singer, songwriter, and actress, Lady Gaga.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="291" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,827]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,512,539]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Discussion.</emphasis>
The new genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Morris &amp; Dietrich, 2020" authorityName="Morris &amp; Dietrich" authorityYear="2020" box="[512,601,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Kaikaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="287" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[512,601,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Kaikaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
most closely resembles members of the Old World tribe Beaufortianini and New World tribes Platycentrini, Boocerini, and Nessorhinini. Although 
<taxonomicName authority="Morris &amp; Dietrich, 2020" authorityName="Morris &amp; Dietrich" authorityYear="2020" box="[968,1057,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Kaikaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="287" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[968,1057,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Kaikaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resembles Beaufortianini in overall external appearance, the structure of the second valvulae suggests a closer relationship to some members of the Caribbean endemic tribe Nessorhinini (
<emphasis box="[667,1098,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[667,808,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Nessorhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nessorhinus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1869" box="[819,948,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Orthobelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Orthobelus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1869" box="[960,1098,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Callicentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Callicentrus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
). The unusual pre-apical cleft of the 3rd valvula is also found in the other endemic Caribbean tribe Monobelini (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[1064,1188,657,683]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Monobelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1064,1188,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Monobelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), some nessorhinines, and in the mainland North American genus 
<taxonomicName box="[644,786,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Platycentrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[644,786,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Platycentrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation box="[801,885,693,719]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,239,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[163,1402,986,1666]" captionText="TABLE 1. Character concepts largely follow those of Wallace and Deitz (2004) and Dietrich et al. (2001). Monobelus is compared rather than Monobelini sensu Wallace and Deitz (2004) because Monobelus has many character states that are not characteristic of the tribe overall." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5D663FD37EFFD16D821178FDCBFC25" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" tableUuid="DF5D663FD37EFFD16D821178FDCBFC25">Table 1</tableCitation>
). The emarginate shape and length of the scutellum (full notch visible in ventral view with abdomen removed) is similar to that found in boocerines, most beaufortianines and some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[397,521,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Monobelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[397,521,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Monobelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike the Boocerini, the most diverse tribe in Central America, 
<taxonomicName authority="Morris &amp; Dietrich, 2020" authorityName="Morris &amp; Dietrich" authorityYear="2020" box="[1281,1370,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Kaikaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="287" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[1281,1370,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Kaikaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks cucullate setae on the mesothoracic femur or tibia (
<tableCitation box="[723,807,801,827]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,239,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[163,1402,986,1666]" captionText="TABLE 1. Character concepts largely follow those of Wallace and Deitz (2004) and Dietrich et al. (2001). Monobelus is compared rather than Monobelini sensu Wallace and Deitz (2004) because Monobelus has many character states that are not characteristic of the tribe overall." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5D663FD37EFFD16D821178FDCBFC25" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" tableUuid="DF5D663FD37EFFD16D821178FDCBFC25">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Table-UUID="DF5D663FD37EFFD16D821178FDCBFC25" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5D663FD37EFFD16D821178FDCBFC25" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" startId="5.[151,239,874,898]" targetBox="[163,1402,986,1666]" targetIsTable="true" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,874,971]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,874,898]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">TABLE 1.</emphasis>
Character concepts largely follow those of 
<bibRefCitation author="Wallace, M. &amp; Deitz, L. L." box="[731,1003,875,899]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" pagination="1 - 337" refId="ref3707" refString="Wallace, M. &amp; Deitz, L. L. (2004) Phylogeny and systematics of the treehopper subfamily Centrotinae (Hemiptera: Membracidae). Memoirs on Entomology International, 19, 1 - 337 + i-iv." type="journal article" year="2004">Wallace and Deitz (2004)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Dietrich, C. H. &amp; McKamey, S. H. &amp; Deitz, L. L." box="[1055,1283,875,899]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" pagination="213 - 39" refId="ref3365" refString="Dietrich, C. H., McKamey, S. H. &amp; Deitz, L. L. (2001). Morphology-based phylogeny of the treehopper family Membracidae (Hemiptera: Cicadomorpha: Membracoidea). Systematic Entomology, 26, 213 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1365 - 3113.2001.00140. x" type="journal article" year="2001">
Dietrich 
<emphasis box="[1149,1196,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">et al</emphasis>
. (2001)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[1293,1412,875,899]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Monobelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1412,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Monobelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<tableNote pageId="5" pageNumber="291" targetBox="[163,1402,986,1666]" targetPageId="5">
compared rather than Monobelini 
<emphasis box="[516,575,911,934]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wallace, M. &amp; Deitz, L. L." box="[582,854,911,935]" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" pagination="1 - 337" refId="ref3707" refString="Wallace, M. &amp; Deitz, L. L. (2004) Phylogeny and systematics of the treehopper subfamily Centrotinae (Hemiptera: Membracidae). Memoirs on Entomology International, 19, 1 - 337 + i-iv." type="journal article" year="2004">Wallace and Deitz (2004)</bibRefCitation>
because 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[953,1072,911,935]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Monobelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[953,1072,911,935]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="291">Monobelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has many character states that are not characteristic of the tribe overall.
</tableNote>
</paragraph>
</caption>
